{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8dc35bc6-3d2d-4b94-b3b5-7ecead1111f0","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads for your current SDK band. After a SDK update, your workloads likely need newer versions to match, so this is the correct fix.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **Reinstalls** workloads at their current versions. It fixes corrupted installations but doesn't change versions, so it won't resolve version mismatches caused by a SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:** Run:\n```\ndotnet workload update\n```\nIf the build still fails afterward, also try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it ensures all workloads declared in your project are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0b8d4faa-e8bf-4625-b63a-50c5a76bd7eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general .NET knowledge question, not tied to any code in the working directory. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the current SDK band. This is what you want after a SDK update, because workloads need to match the SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but does **not** change versions.\n\n\n- After a .NET SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the command to run since it syncs your workloads with the new SDK version.","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"A422:2231E4:5BC44F9:643D0BC:69F0045E"},"id":"45589731-700f-48fa-a338-43d7d4ca45b9","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:50:46.993Z","parentId":"ec929ecb-1d44-4f61-8b12-3eadab98b990"}
